'''Junseok "Andy"{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} Lee''' ({{ko-hhrm|이준석}}) is a South Korean [[entrepreneur]] and a founder of Edushare, an educational service organization. He was one of the 11-member [[Grand National Party]]’s (later Saenuri Party then [[Liberty Korea Party]]) Leadership Council, being the youngest member ever to sit on the Council that was given the power to overhaul the Party.<ref>[http://www.koreaherald.com/national/Detail.jsp?newsMLId=20111228000921 26 year old grabs spotlight among new GNP leaders]</ref>
==Education== Lee studied in an American school in Indonesia for one year,<ref>[http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/society/society_general/512645.html 한나라 비대위원 이준석 아버지, 유승민 의원과 친구]</ref> and later attended and graduated from [[Seoul Science High School]]. Once admitted to [[KAIST]], Lee transferred to [[Harvard University]] and received a [[Bachelor's degree|B.A.]] in [[Economics]] and [[Computer Science]].
==Work Experience== Lee interned as [[South Korea|South Korean]] lawmaker [[Yoo Seong-min]]'s assistant.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}
In lieu of military service, he did [[Alternative civilian service|alternative service]] at Innotive, an IT firm owned by [[Nexon]], as a junior [[software engineer]]. During his service he founded Edushare, a service organization similar to [[Teach for America]] to provide academic services to students who are a part of low-income families.<ref>[https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2011/12/116_101751.html Young start-up CEO steals show]</ref> Lee first began the organization by an online plea in Seoul Science High Alumni website to recruit volunteers.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}
In 2010, he founded ClasseStudio, an online education [[startup company|startup]] along with the people he met at Innotive.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}
==Grand National Party Leadership Council== Handpicked by Rep. [[Park Geun-hye]], the party’s leading presidential candidate, Lee Jun-seok is the youngest ever to hold a leadership position in the history of the conservative ruling party. Being a part of the Leadership Council, Lee's role was to make key decisions on behalf of the party, including the selection of candidates to run in the parliamentary elections in April. Pundits view the appointment to appeal to the younger demographic and counter the surging popularity of [[Ahn Cheol-soo]].<ref>[http://www.arirang.co.kr/News/News_View.asp?nseq=124109&code=Ne2&category=2 GNP's New Leadership Holds First Official Meeting; DUP Pledge to Achieve Fair Elections]</ref> Lee's background in computer science and a track record of public service resemble those of Ahn and some see that as the reason for the appointment. Lee remained as a member of [[Liberty Korea Party|Saenuri Party]] after Park Geun-hye became the [[President of South Korea]].
==After corruption scandal in 2016== During [[2016 South Korean political scandal]], Lee harshly criticized the former president Park Geun-hye, whom Lee supported at [[South Korean presidential election, 2012|18th presidential election]]. Lee quit [[Liberty Korea Party|Saenuri Party]] (currently renamed as [[Liberty Korea Party]]) and joined [[Bareun Party]] with conservative lawmakers who had opposed Park.
==Controversies== Lee's background and comments have been reported heavily in the Korean media upon his appointment. Recently he asked the host of "[[I'm a Weasel]]", a progressive and popular podcast for political satire and criticism of the conservative Grand National Party, for help to investigate the political scandal that is plaguing the Grand National Party. [[Kang Yong-suk]], a national assemblyman made some attacks on Junseok Lee's qualifications. The critics of the Grand National Party argue that Junseok Lee's old Tweets show his indifference to the average Korean and that he belongs to the upper elite as his Harvard education shows. Lee's tweet that stated "The National Council of the Victims of Forced Eviction must be mentally retarded" was viewed as evidence of his indifference and created particularly harsh criticisms.<ref>[http://biz.heraldm.com/common/Detail.jsp?newsMLId=20111230000172 SBS 정성근 앵커, “이준석, 강용석과 같은 과”]</ref> Lee apologized for the remark and his uncontrolled emotions.<ref>[http://joongang.joinsmsn.com/article/834/7018834.html?ctg=1000&cloc=joongang|article|outside_home 이준석 "박근혜, 의혹 신속히 털고 가야"]</ref>
